We categorize those FL methods into two groups: loss-based and data augmentation-based methods. The first set of methods aims to regularize the local models by modifying the local training loss to mitigate biasÂ (Li etÂ al., 2020b; Shi etÂ al., 2022; Zhang etÂ al., 2022a; Lee etÂ al., 2022). However, these methods face significant challenges when dealing with limited local data since they require a balance between local optimization and global knowledge preservation. In Sec.Â 3.1, we demonstrate that the state-of-the-art loss-based methods under-perform as data scarcity increases.
The second category of those methods proposes exchanging a global data proxy, such as a portion of raw data, aggregated data, or synthetic data, along with sharing model parametersÂ (Zhao etÂ al., 2018; Yoon etÂ al., 2020; Liu etÂ al., 2022). Although these methods tend to outperform the loss-based approaches in the presence of data scarcity, performance improvement often comes at the cost of added privacy vulnerabilities. For example, FedMixÂ (Yoon etÂ al., 2020) shares average (over mini-batches) data samples, which may reveal sensitive information consistently embedded in the entire batch of data (as illustrated in Sec.Â 3.3).
As summarized in TableÂ 1, our work, for the first time in the literature, addresses the challenges posed by data scarcity and label skew simultaneously, while preserving data privacy.

Data reconstruction. We first implemented a data reconstruction attacker, following the approach described inÂ Dosovitskiy & Brox (2016), the attacker constructed a decoder for the purpose of reconstruction. Specifically, the attacker targeted the converged global model trained using the Quantity(333) distribution, ensuring a fair comparison. The decoder architecture, designed to match the MobileNet_V2 architecture, comprised four conv2d layers (refer to TableÂ 10) to reconstruct the original data from the provided features. For visualization purposes, the CIFAR101010 images were cropped to a size of 32Ã—32323232\times 32 pixels without any normalization. The decoder took the features extracted from the global model as input and generated a reconstructed image, which served as the basis for calculating the mean squared error (MSE).

The analysis for TableÂ 6 is elaborated on as follows. Among loss-based approaches, FedNTD is the best, showing a strong ability to handle data scarcity and label skew (about 10%percent1010\% improvement from FedAvg), while other loss-based FL methods present marginal gain from FedAvg. The outstanding performance of FedNTD are mainly attributed to its knowledge distillation component, mitigating the local over-fitting as well as model bias. FLea further improves FedNTD by 3âˆ¼5%similar-to3percent53\sim 5\% when the average local data size is 500500500, and the superiority of FLea is more remarkable with increasing level of data scarcity, e.g., when the average local data size reduces to 100100100, the performance gain reaches 17.6%percent17.617.6\% (Dirichlet(0.1) group).

More reflection for FedNTD. From both FigureÂ 1 and TableÂ 6, we can see FedNTD is a strong baseline for both data scarcity and label skew.
FedNTD was devised to address the non-IID setting, but we find it is also able to alleviate issues with data scarcity in the IID setting. This suggests global knowledge distilling can mitigate local over-fitting. However, as the data becomes scarce, the distillation ability declines, herein the performance gain drops. Instead of using local data for knowledge distilling, in FLea, we leverage the augmented features to distill the knowledge from the global model into the local model.

We also discuss the impact of layer lğ‘™l, from which layer the features are extracted. It is a trade-off between between privacy protection and the utilization of features.
A smaller lğ‘™l indicates the features are closer to the raw data while the privacy vulnerability increases. In Sec.Â 5.3, we have demonstrated that l=5ğ‘™5l=5 with the de-correlation loss can well defend against privacy attacks in our simulations. In TableÂ 8, we also show that sharing features from l=1ğ‘™1l=1 can enhance FLea while from l=9ğ‘™9l=9 can lead to a slight performance decline. For real-world applications (beyond CIFAR101010), we choose lğ‘™l according to the specific performance and privacy requirements. It is also worth mentioning that, as FLea is designed to leverage the latest feature buffer, lğ‘™l wonâ€™t necessarily to be fixed. On the contrary, lğ‘™l can be dynamically altered during training based on the performance and privacy requirements.
